// Definition:
// A Higher Order Component (HOC) is a function that accepts a component and returns a new enhanced component.
// Syntax
// const EnhancedComponent = HigherOrderComponent(OriginalComponent);

// Why are HOCs Used?
//HOCs help to reuse the same logic across multiple components without repeating code.
// Reasons for using HOCs
// Reuse common logic
// Avoid duplicate code
// Add extra functionality
// Improve code maintainability
// Separate business logic from UI

// HOC
// Enhances a component
// Older React Pattern
// Reuse component logic
// Functional & Class Components
// New Component
// Medium
// Less
// Wrapper component added
// Less Common

// Hook
// Reuses logic inside functional components
// React 16.8
// Reuse stateful logic
// Functional Components Only
// State/Functions
// Easy
// More
// Better
// Most Preferred

//Component Composition
// Combines components together
// Core React Concept
// Build UI layouts
// Functional & Class Components
// JSX Components
// Easy
// More
// Better
// Very Common